= Consonance, Synchronicity and Mirror Effect
#v(15pt)
When two rhythmic layers subdivide the beat at different rates, their relationship can be understood in terms of how often their cycles realign. This perspective — borrowed from the physics of periodic signals — allows us to speak of rhythmic consonance and dissonance in a precise and meaningful way: two subdivision systems are rhythmically consonant to the degree that their beat cycles frequently coincide. A central finding of this chapter is that swing can serve as a tuning mechanism between otherwise unrelated subdivision systems. By distorting the internal spacing of each layer's subdivisions, it becomes possible to bring their cycles into alignment — or to maintain that alignment across the entire range of swing amounts. This latter phenomenon, which we call the mirror effect, is examined in detail: we identify the conditions under which paired swinging systems preserve their synchronicity throughout morphing, and introduce practical approaches for experiencing and performing the mirror on an instrument.

